Here, let me help you:
[quote][h]Types of Rolls[/h]Skill Roll: used for Skills, along with things that are [i]like[/i] skills (such as the Esolang.) Usually boosted by skill boosts.
Luck Roll: used for things related to sheer luck, such as fish type and the filling of a Heart-Shaped Chocolate. Commonly boosted by an equipped Four-Leaf Clover.
Sticker Roll: a 1d40, rolled when you do something that might net you a sticker. A result of 31 to 39 nets you a regular sticker, while a result of 40 nets you a raised sticker. Can't be boosted.
Upgrade Roll: like a Sticker Roll, but for summon/ally upgrades instead. A result of 31 or above nets you an upgrade. Can't be boosted.
Strength Roll: a roll based on your Strength stat. Similar rolls exist for all your other RPG stats (i.e. INT, AGI, CHR, DEX, CON.) Boosted by Strength only.
Attack Roll: signifies the base damage done by an attack. Based off of the attacker's Indirect and Direct Attack.
Damage Roll: like the attack roll, but caused by something else (such as fall damage.) Based off of the damage source.
Defense Roll: signifies the damage that is not taken due to defending. Based off of the defender's Indirect and Direct Defense.
Effect Roll: determines what effect, if any, on will get from an action (such as being attacked, or drinking a potion,) or whether an effect will take action. A sub-roll of the Luck Roll.
Accuracy Roll: determines whether an attack will hit the target. Can't be boosted, but the target can be lowered.
Fish Roll: determines what category of fish you get. A sub-roll of the Luck Roll.
Item Roll: determines what item you get from a drop table. Can't be boosted.
Weather Roll: a 1d20, which determines what the weather will be like next turn, relative to the current weather. Player independent.
Rain Roll: a 1d10, which determines what growth boost a crop will get from the rain. Player independent.
Candy Roll: determines what item you get from an Item Candy. A sub-roll of the Item Roll.
Mob Roll: used to determine what mobs will spawn, and what those mobs will do. Player independent.
Target Roll: determines what will be targeted by something (usually an attack.)
Loot Roll: a 1d100, which determines whether a killed mob will drop a specific item. A sub-roll of the Luck roll.
Count Roll: determined how many targets will be hit. Usually player independent.
Ignition Roll: seen during Turn 59, determines whether something will explode. Player independent.
Fire Roll: a 1d10, determines whether an item will burn due to fire. Can't be boosted.
Fall Damage Roll: seen during Turn 22, obsolete (would use Damage Roll now)
Option Roll: seen during Turn 29, synonym of Target Roll
Plant Roll: seen during Turns 37 to 39, synonym of Rain Roll
Structure Roll: seen during Turns 37 to 39, determines what Structures get Soaked by rain, obsolete (would use Rain Roll now)
Player Roll: seen during Turns 37 to 39, determines what players get Soaked by rain, obsolete (would use Rain Roll now)
Paralysis Roll: seen during Turn 42, determines whether Paralysis takes effect, obsolete (would use Effect Roll now)
Theft Roll: seen during Turn 65, a 1d20 that determines whether you successfully steal an item from someone. A sub-roll of the Luck roll, additionally boosted by Agility.[/quote]
Hope that helps!
